benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/auditLogsWithHistory - Retrieve account audit logs with history by account id

covered: Valid Request: TC01 and TC12 validate successful retrieval and presence of mandatory AuditLog fields.
Empty Response: TC02 verifies the API returns an empty JSON array when no audit logs exist.
Error Responses: TC03 (404), TC04 (400), TC05/TC06 (401), and TC07 (500) cover standard error scenarios.
Unsupported Query Parameters: TC08 checks that extra/unsupported parameters are ignored.
Security: TC10 covers injection attempt handling and protection of sensitive info.
Performance/Load: TC09 and TC11 address large history and concurrent request behavior/performance expectations.
Edge Cases: TC14–TC17 cover whitespace, case-sensitivity, max-length UUID, and partial-id formats.
Integration/Dependency: TC13 covers degraded downstream dependency behavior (service slow/unavailable).
Regression: TC12 ensures previously fixed missing-field bugs remain fixed.
gaps: Pagination: No tests verify pagination semantics (limit/offset or page links), headers (Link), or behavior when result sets exceed a page.
Caching Behavior: No scenarios verify caching headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control) or conditional GET behavior (304).
Rate Limiting / Throttling: No tests exercise rate limits or expect 429 responses under abusive request rates (TC11 checks concurrency/performance but not rate-limit responses).
Authorization nuances: Tests cover missing/invalid tokens (401) but do not cover forbidden access (403) or role/scope-based authorization differences.
Deep Schema Validation: Field-level validation (types, formats, timestamps, expected value constraints, nested history structure) is not asserted beyond presence.
Query Parameters — positive cases: Only unsupported params are tested; there are no tests for valid/optional query params (filters, sort, date ranges) or their validation.
Content Negotiation & Headers: No tests for Accept header handling, character encoding, or other relevant response headers beyond Content-Type.
Recovery / Data Integrity after Security Test: TC10 asserts DB remains intact conceptually, but there is no explicit verification step to confirm data integrity after malicious input.
recommendations: Add pagination tests: create account audit logs > typical page size and verify paging parameters, Link headers, limit/offset behavior, and consistency across pages.
Add caching/conditional GET tests: verify ETag/Last-Modified presence, conditional requests (If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since) return 304 when appropriate, and Cache-Control policies.
Add explicit rate-limiting tests: simulate high request rates to assert proper throttling behavior and expected 429 or backoff responses (and verify retry headers if present).
Add authorization role/scope tests: include scenarios for authenticated but unauthorized users (403), and verify behavior for different permission levels.
Add deeper schema/contract checks: validate field types, timestamp formats, user IDs, action enums, and nested history contents against the API definition (not just presence).
Add positive query-parameter tests if API supports them: filters (by date range, event type), sorting, limits, and combinations; also test invalid parameter values return 400 with helpful messages.
Add content-negotiation and header tests: ensure Accept header handling, correct charset, and no unexpected headers; verify response Content-Type for error responses too.
Enhance security verification: after injection or malformed-path tests, include automated checks to confirm database integrity and no leakage of sensitive stack traces in responses.
